#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:11
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating Custom Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:12
#, no-c-format
msgid "For creating your custom image you need a base docker image of &slsa;. You can use any of the pre-built &slsa; images that you can obtain as described in <xref linkend=\"Customizing_Pre-build_Images\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:18
#, no-c-format
msgid "No &slsa; Images in Docker Hub"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:19
#, no-c-format
msgid "Usually you can pull a variety of base docker images from the <link xlink:href=\"https://hub.docker.com/\">docker hub</link> but that does not apply for &slsa;. Currently we cannot distribute &slsa; images for Docker because there is no way to associate an End-User License Agreement (EULA) to a Docker image. <literal>sle2docker</literal> enables you to import pre-built &slsa; images that you can use for creating base &slsa; images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:29
#, no-c-format
msgid "After you obtain your base docker image, you can modify the image by using a <filename>Dockerfile</filename> (usually placed in the build directory). Then use the standard docker building tool to create your custom image:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;docker build <replaceable>PATH_TO_BUILD_DIRECTORY</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:35
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about <literal>docker build</literal> options, see the <link xlink:href=\"https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/build/\">official Docker documentation</link>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:41
#, no-c-format
msgid "Dockerizing Your Applications"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:42
#, no-c-format
msgid "You may want to write a dockerfile for your own application that should be run inside a docker container. For a procedure refer to <xref linkend=\"docker.dockerizing.application\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:68
#, no-c-format
msgid "Obtaining Base &slsa; Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:70
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can install pre-built images of &slsa; by using Zypper:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:74
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper in sles11sp4-docker-image suse-sles12sp3-image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:76
#, no-c-format
msgid "Pre-built images do not have repositories configured. But when the Docker host has an SLE subscription that provides access to the product used in the image, Zypper will automatically have access to the right repositories."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:82
#, no-c-format
msgid "After the pre-built images are installed, you need to list them using <literal>sle2docker</literal> to get a proper image name:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:87
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;sle2docker list"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:89
#, no-c-format
msgid "Now you need to activate the pre-built images:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:93
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;sle2docker activate <replaceable>PRE-BUILT_IMAGE_NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:95
#, no-c-format
msgid "After successful activation, <literal>sle2docker</literal> will display the name of the docker image. You can customize the docker image as described in <xref linkend=\"Customizing_Pre-build_Images\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:102
#, no-c-format
msgid "Customizing &slsa; Docker Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:104
#, no-c-format
msgid "The pre-built images do not have any repository configured and do not include any modules or extensions. They contain a <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/SUSE/container-suseconnect\">zypper service</link> that contacts either the SUSE Customer Center (SCC) or your Subscription Management Tool (SMT) server, according to the configuration of the SLE host that runs the Docker container. The service obtains the list of repositories available for the product used by the Docker image. You can also directly declare extensions in your <filename>Dockerfile</filename> (for details refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.docker.sle_images.customizing_the_images.extensions\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:117
#, no-c-format
msgid "You do not need to add any credentials to the Docker image because the machine credentials are automatically injected into the container by the docker daemon. They are injected inside of the <literal>/run/secrets</literal> directory. The same applies to the <filename>/etc/SUSEConnect</filename> file of the host system, which is automatically injected into the <filename>/run/secrets</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid "Credentials and Security"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:129
#, no-c-format
msgid "The contents of the <filename>/run/secrets</filename> directory are never committed to a Docker image, hence there is no risk of your credentials leaking."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:136
#, no-c-format
msgid "To obtain the list of repositories, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper ref -s"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:141
#, no-c-format
msgid "It will automatically add all the repositories to your container. For each repository added to the system a new file will be created under <command>/etc/zypp/repos.d</command>. The URLs of these repositories include an access token that automatically expires after 12 hours. To renew the token call the <command>zypper ref -s</command> command. It is secure to commit these files to a Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:150
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you want to use a different set of credentials, place a custom <filename>/etc/zypp/credentials.d/SCCcredentials</filename> file inside of the Docker image. It contains the machine credentials that have the subscription you want to use. The same applies to the <filename>SUSEConnect</filename> file: to override the file available on the host system that is running the Docker container, add a custom <filename>/etc/SUSEConnect</filename> file inside of the Docker image."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:160
#, no-c-format
msgid "Now you can create a custom Docker image by using a <literal>Dockerfile</literal>. If you want to create a custom &slea;&nbsp;12 image, please refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.docker.sle_images.customizing_the_images.sles12\"/>. If you want to create a custom &slea;&nbsp;11 SP3 Docker image, please refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.docker.sle_images.customizing_the_images.sles11sp3\"/>. In case you would like to move your application to a Docker container, please refer to <xref linkend=\"docker.dockerizing.application\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:172
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating a Custom &slea;&nbsp;12 Image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following Docker file creates a simple Docker image based on &slea;&nbsp;12 SP3:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:177
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
      "FROM suse/sles12sp3:latest\n"
      "\n"
      "RUN zypper ref -s\n"
      "RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:178 docker_building_images.xml:192
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the Docker host machine is registered against an internal &rmt; server, the Docker image requires the SSL certificate used by &rmt;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
      "FROM suse/sles12sp3:latest\n"
      "\n"
      "# Import the crt file of our private SMT server\n"
      "ADD http://smt.test.lan/smt.crt /etc/pki/trust/anchors/smt.crt\n"
      "RUN update-ca-certificates\n"
      "\n"
      "RUN zypper ref -s\n"
      "RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:186
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating a Custom &slea;&nbsp;11 SP3 Image"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:187
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following Docker file creates a simple Docker image based on &slea;&nbsp;11 SP4:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:191
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
      "FROM suse/sles11sp3:latest\n"
      "\n"
      "RUN zypper ref -s\n"
      "RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:196
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
      "FROM suse/sles11sp4:latest\n"
      "\n"
      "# Import the crt file of our private SMT server\n"
      "ADD http://smt.test.lan/smt.crt /etc/ssl/certs/smt.pem\n"
      "RUN c_rehash /etc/ssl/certs\n"
      "\n"
      "RUN zypper ref -s\n"
      "RUN zypper -n in vim"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:200
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adding &slea; Extensions and Modules to Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:201
#, no-c-format
msgid "You may have subscriptions to SLE extensions or modules that you would like to use in your custom image. To add them to the Docker image, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: docker_building_images.xml:207
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adding Extension and Modules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:209
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the following into your <filename>Dockerfile</filename>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: docker_building_images.xml:212
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
      "ADD *.repo /etc/zypp/repos.d/\n"
      "ADD *.service /etc/zypp/services.d\n"
      "RUN zypper refs &amp;&amp; zypper refresh"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: docker_building_images.xml:215
#, no-c-format
msgid "Copy all <filename>.service</filename> and <filename>.repo</filename> files that you will use into the directory where you will build the Docker image from the <filename>Dockerfile</filename>."
msgstr ""

